name: East Hamongog
description:
Introduction

This canyon was first explored on 7/23/23 with a team of 4. As the finish to the trifecta (second hamongog & upper fort creek), we saved the best for last. Two team members joined us for this final route. It turned out to be better than imagined, and what I think is one of the best in the region. This route will require a lot of effort compared to anything else in the Wasatch. 2+ hour approach, 2000' vert, thick vegetation, bees (we all got a few stings), etc. But well worth it for the adventurous soul.

The canyon was ghosted using a fiddle (rated 4 for advanced rigging currently). Future teams may decide to place webbing, though it isn't necessary. So please try to keep it as pristine as possible.

Second descent 8/12/23 as a team of 4, doing the full drainage from Lake Hardy.

Approach

The main road is North Three Falls Way, and the turn off to the trailhead has a "no trespassing" sign (north aspen drive). Driving this dirt road takes you to the TH parking, which appears to be legal by all the locals. This is where we parked. Starting your hike past the gate, you will stay on the dirt east of Schoolhouse Springs. From the SHS approach it is 2.1 miles and 2100' of gain to get to the drainage, hiking up to the First Hamongog and then continuing east up past the East Hamongog. When you get to the creek, head down the drainage, paralleling the creek until (with some small downclimbs) until you get to rap1.

Descent

r1: 30'

r2: 30'

r3: 80' (2-stage)

r4: 40'

r5: 100'

r6: 100'

r7: 60'

r8: 100'

r9: 80'

r10: 80'

Exit

After a few exploration runs, an easy exit option was found by heading directly south up and over to Dry Creek. You will cross over another short drainage, and on the second ridge you will find a clear trail leading you down to the private property. Once you see the fence/boundary turn left and stay on the east side down to Dry Creek. Cross over the creek and head to the parking lot.

Red tape

Avoid following the creek into the private property.
